        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sep 18. 1868</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged to you for your great kindness in taking the trouble to send me the facts about the coloured grapes; but I need not ask you to take any further trouble as I have already heard of several analogous cases—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Some cases are given in the chapter on Bud-variation in my last published book—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>With my thanks | I remain dear Sir | yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 16, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6371.xml">letter from J. S. Bristowe, 17 September 1868</ref>. Bristowe had written about a grapevine that bore different coloured grapes.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 375 and 399–400. <hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> was published in early 1868.</note>
        </div>
    
